      "content": "While opponents claim redistribution punishes individual hard work, a truly fair approach would not strip assets from proven actors but rather reallocate legacy wealth accumulated over generations through systemic advantages, effectively prioritizing equity without necessarily punishing merit. Redefining fairness to mean \"equal opportunity\" rather than \"equal outcome\" supports redistribution by ensuring that everyone starts from a genuine footing, which actually enhances the ability of all individuals to demonstrate their personal ingenuity and labor. Ignoring this distinction allows the privileged to frame equity as theft, when in reality, democratizing wealth creation empowers those without resources to build their own meritocratic success from the ground up. Therefore, defending redistribution as a tool for racial justice is not an attack on hard work, but a necessary precondition for it to ever occur equally for everyone regardless of their ancestral background.",
